{
  "query": "How does the success of providing artificial nest sites for solitary bees compare to providing them for bumblebees?",
  "relevant_summary": "Artificial nest sites for solitary bees show much higher success rates and occupancy compared to bumblebee nest boxes. For solitary bees, 29 out of 30 replicated trials showed occupancy by bees, with many species readily using nest boxes including endangered species. Occupancy rates for solitary bee nest boxes ranged from 1-26% of available cavities, and studies demonstrated that nest provision could double the number of occupied nests over three years. In contrast, bumblebee nest boxes showed very low uptake rates of 2% or less in recent UK trials, with only 0-2.5% occupancy in three replicated trials since 1989. While some older trials (pre-1978) showed higher bumblebee occupancy rates of 10-48%, current evidence indicates underground nest boxes are most effective for bumblebees with 6-58% occupancy, whereas surface wooden boxes commonly marketed for gardens show very low success rates of 0-1.5%.",
