  "relevant_summary": "Several methods have been tested to control non-native species and pests affecting bees. For invasive honey bee control, one replicated trial in Louisiana demonstrated that Africanized honey bee colonies can be killed by providing insecticide (acephate)-laced syrup for 30 minutes. Another replicated controlled trial in Japan attempted to eradicate European buff-tailed bumblebees by catching and killing foraging bees, which led to increased numbers of two native bumblebee species, though it did not achieve full eradication. For small hive beetle control, a replicated trial in the USA tested mite-killing strips in commercial honey bee transport packages, but found that more than half the beetles escaped and were not killed. Additionally, ectoparasite removal from nests has been investigated, with six of seven studies finding lower infestation rates in treated nests.",
