{
  "query": "What is the evidence regarding the timeframe for bee colonization of newly created nesting habitats?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from action documents shows that bee colonization of newly created nesting habitats can occur rapidly. One replicated controlled trial in Germany and four small trials demonstrated that artificially exposed areas of bare soil can be successfully colonized by ground-nesting solitary bees and wasps within the first or second year. For artificial nest sites, 29 out of 30 replicated trials across 10 countries showed that solitary bee nest boxes were occupied by bees, indicating prompt colonization once suitable nesting sites are provided. The documents indicate that many species of solitary bee will readily nest in newly provided artificial nest boxes, including endangered species, with some studies showing that the number of occupied solitary bee nests can double over three years with repeated nest box provision at given sites.",
