{
  "query": "What interventions are available to improve nesting habitat for ground-nesting bees?",
  "relevant_summary": "Several interventions are available to improve nesting habitat for ground-nesting bees based on the evidence reviewed. The primary intervention is creating patches of bare ground, which five studies (four replicated trials and one un replicated study) showed can be successfully colonized by ground-nesting solitary bees and wasps within one to two years. However, there is no evidence demonstrating the effect of bare ground creation on bee populations or communities at larger scales. For cavity-nesting solitary bees, providing artificial nest sites has been extensively tested across 30 replicated trials in 10 countries, with 29 trials showing successful occupancy by various bee species. Nest boxes made from cut hollow stems, tubes, or drilled wooden blocks are readily occupied and can increase local bee populations when placed within 150-600m of foraging resources. Repeated nest box provision at sites over three years can double the number of occupied solitary bee nests. Bumblebee nest boxes have shown very low uptake rates of 0-2.5% in recent studies, with underground designs performing better than surface boxes, but overall effectiveness remains limited for ground-nesting bumblebees.",
  "action_ids": [
    "13",
    "47",
    "80",
    "48"
  ]
}

