{
  "query": "What is the state of the evidence regarding the success of captive rearing and subsequent reintroduction of bumblebees into the wild?",
  "relevant_summary": "The evidence regarding captive rearing and reintroduction of bumblebees shows mixed results. Seven replicated trials have monitored laboratory-reared colonies introduced to the wild, with variable success in queen production - some colonies producing very low or zero queens, while others produced good numbers. Social parasitism by cuckoo bees is a significant issue, with rates ranging from 25-79% in trials. Supplementary feeding showed mixed effects on colony productivity. Captive rearing protocols have been developed for declining species, with some success in inducing queens to rear adults for certain species, but complete failure for others like the yellow bumblebee B. fervidus where eggs were laid but larvae died before becoming adults. There is no evidence found for the effects of reintroducing laboratory-reared bumblebee queens specifically.",
