{
  "query": "What evidence exists for the effectiveness of bee conservation actions in human-managed, non-agricultural settings like gardens, road verges, and areas under power lines?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from multiple studies shows that bee conservation actions in human-managed, non-agricultural settings can be effective. In gardens, two replicated trials in the USA and Canada found more wild bee species and individuals in gardens planted with bee forage or native plants compared to conventionally managed gardens, and a UK site comparison study found more bumblebee species in domestic city gardens with lower management intensity. For road verges, a replicated paired site comparison study in the USA found that restored roadside prairies where herbicide application was restricted had greater species richness and abundance of butterflies compared to verges dominated by non-native vegetation with no herbicide restrictions. Areas under power lines showed similar results, with a replicated site comparison study in Canada finding that transmission lines (including power lines) which were neither sprayed with herbicide nor mown had greater abundance of northern pearl crescent and pearl crescent butterflies compared to sprayed and mown areas. Altering mowing regimes by reducing mowing frequency or timing also proved effective, with replicated studies in the UK and Canada finding higher abundance of adult butterflies in unmown public parks and road verges compared to regularly mown areas, and a replicated site comparison study in Poland finding fewer dead butterflies on less frequently mown road verges.",
